Sum is 0.31 because there is rounding in sum and only 2 decimal digits are stored.
Why is this?
When you are dealing with money, which is what I understand 0.1 to be, 2 decimal digits are sometimes not enough to fully understand the value, e.g. (0.1 + 0.2 == 0.3) may be considered a general rule.
If you are looking for another general rule, this might be helpful for you, too: How do decimal numbers get represented in computers ?.
0.1 is a repeating decimal fraction that isn't exactly representable in a binary floating-point format, and a similar issue has arisen for other decimal fractions.
