A memory leak occurs when memory is not being properly freed or released in a computer program, which can lead to memory being allocated, used, temporarily unavailable and then lost. If a memory leak happens, it can cause programs to consume an increasing amount of memory, potentially leading to slow performance or system crashing. To detect a memory leak, it's important to check the memory usage of the program, conduct debugging, and test for any unnecessary object creation and proper object disposal.</a>

